1.a

The K-fold cross validation is implemented by randomly splitting data into K subset without overlaps. Each time one subset is chosen to serve as test set and the rest as training set. We repeat this process for K times and the the estimated MSE is the average MSEs of each process.

1.b

i.

The validation set approach is simpler compared to K-fold, which is computationally more expensive. But the MSE variance and bias are higher due to the selection of validation set. When the test set size is too small, it may largely overestimate the MSE. #ii. LOOCV is more computationally expensive than K-fold, for it’s the extreme case of K-fold when K equals to sample size. And the variance of MSEs for LOOCV process is higher than MSEs generated for K-folds as well, but it’s more robust regarding to the bias caused by randomness of data splitting.

2.a

The probability of chosing the \(jth\) element in the observations of size \(n\) is \(1/n\). So the probability of not selecting this element as the first bootstrap element is \(1-\frac{1}{n}\).

2.b

It’s still \(1-\frac{1}{n}\), because we put the element back when bootstrapping.

2.c

When boostrapping, we repeat selecting elements from observations with putting back \(n\) times. These \(n\) processes are independent from each other. For each of them, the probability of \(jth\) element not selected is \(1-\frac{1}{n}\). Therefore, repeating the same process for \(n\) times, the probability of \(jth\) element not selected is \((1-\frac{1}{n})^n\)

2.d

\(P(jth\in boostrap|n=5) = 1-P(jth\not\in boostrap|n=5)\); We have \(P(jth\not\in boostrap|n=5) = (1-\frac{1}{5})^5\), so \(P(jth\in boostrap|n=5) = 1-(1-\frac{1}{5})^5 \approxeq 67.2\%\)

2.e

\(P(jth\in boostrap|n=100) = 1-(1-\frac{1}{100})^{100} \approxeq 63.4\%\)

2.f

\(P(jth\in boostrap|n=10000) = 1-(1-\frac{1}{10000})^{10000} \approxeq 63.2\%\)

2.g

We can see from the plot that when the sample size is really small the probability of not having one element in bootstrap set is higher, but the probability drop to around 63.2% very fast and stays at 63.2% even if n keep increasing.

n = 1:10^5
g = function(n){ return(1 - (1 - 1/n)^n)}
plot(n, g(n))

2.h

For 100 times different bootstrapping, we got approximately 68 out of 100 bootstrap sets with at least one the 4th element. This is within the acceptable variance range comparing to the true probability, which is 63.4%.

3.d

LOOCV <-NULL
for(i in 1:nrow(Weekly)){
  #leave one out cross validation
  Weekly.train<-Weekly[-i, ]
  Weekly.test<-Weekly[i, ]
  #train the model
  model_3d <- glm(I(Direction=='Up') ~ Lag1+Lag2, family = 'binomial', data=Weekly.train)
  #predict the test set, calculate posterior proba and then map it to a class
  yhat = ifelse(predict(model_3d, newdata=Weekly.test, type='response') > .5, 'Up', 'Down')
  #compare to the ground truth
  if( Weekly.test$Direction == yhat) LOOCV<-rbind(LOOCV,1)
  else LOOCV<-rbind(LOOCV,0)
}

data <- data.frame(x=x, y=y)

4.b

The relationship between predictor and response is nonlinear. According to the model description, the relationship between predictor and response is a second order polynomial, so theoretically a second order polynomial model should fit the data best.

plot(x,y)

4.c

i,ii,iii

K = 5
KCV <-NULL
for(i in 1:4){
  data<- data %>%
    mutate(fold = sample( rep(1:5, times=ceiling(100/5))[1:100]  ))
  for(k in 1:K){
    index <- which( data$fold == k )
    train <- data[ -index, ]
    test  <- data[  index, ]
    model <- lm( y ~ poly(x,i), data=train)
    data[index,'yhat']  <- predict(model, newdata=test)
  }
  KCV <- rbind(KCV,data.frame(order=i, K=K, MSE = mean( (data$y - data$yhat)^2 )))
}

4.d

It’s different from the result in 4.c. This is because every time when we partition the observations into K non-overlapped subset we randomly generate the index. The seed for generate random number is different for 4.c and 4.d, so we end up with different K subsets, which gives us different results.

K = 5

4.f

For K-fold CV, the second order polynomial (most of the times) model or third order polynomial (sometimes) has the lowest MSE, the same conclusion holds for LOOCV as well. This is expected because the true model which generates this data is a second order polynomial

4.g

I used residual resampling for model selection in this case. In the plot, we can get the same conclusion as in 4.f.

for(i in 1:4){
# Do residual resampling with the regression example
model <- lm( y ~ poly(x,i), data=data )
data <- data %>% mutate(
  fitted = fitted(model),
  resid  = resid(model))

# Define the statisitc I care about
my.stat <- function(sample.data, indices){
  data.star <- sample.data %>% mutate(y = fitted + resid[indices])
  model.star <- lm(y ~ x, data=data.star)
  output <- summary(model.star)$sigma
  return(output)
}

boot.model <- boot(data, my.stat, R=100)
hist(boot.model, layout=c(1,3))
}
